===Etymology 1===
Sense of sleeping berth possibly from Scottish English {{term|bunker||seat, bench}}, origin is uncertain but possibly Scandanavian. Confer Old Swedish {{term|bunke||boards used to protect the cargo of a ship|lang=}}. See also {{term|boaring}}, {{term|flooring}} and confer {{term|bunch}}. 

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{nautical}} A [[built-in]] [[bed]] on board [[ship]], often [[erected]] in [[tier]]s one above the other.
# {{military}} A [[cot]].
# One of a series of [[berth]]s or bed places in tiers.
# {{US}} A wooden case or box, which serves for a seat in the daytime and for a bed at night.
# {{US|colloquial}} A piece of wood placed on a lumberman's sled to sustain the end of heavy timbers.

